The course provides an overview of how political systems, institutions and ideologies have developed in the Estonian territory from the second half of the 19th century to the early 2000s. Overall, the course seeks to understand the history of the formation of the Estonian state and society today.
Among the central themes are the development of the Estonian national movement and the evolving idea of nation-statehood, the reception of political ideologies, the formation and development of political parties, different political systems and debates on democracy, ideas of legal continuity, and Estonia as a transition state. Each week, students will also have the opportunity to delve deeper into a specific case study, which will contribute to a deeper understanding of the overall theme.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to provide an overview of the formation and development of political systems, institutions and ideologies in the Estonian territory from the second half of the 19th century to the early 2000s.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  On successful completion of the course, the student: - will have a basic knowledge of the development of institutions, political systems and ideologies in the Estonian territory over the last 150 years in relation to international developments; - is able to analyse provided sources and relate them to historical and contemporary issues; - is able to participate in a discussion on central themes of Estonian political and intellectual history and is capable of formulating proper arguments; - is able to communicate the results of their research in a written form in a clearly argued and structured way, drawing on relevant sources.
